The True Long March
Every nation has its founding myth.
For communist China, it is the Long March – a story that is comparable to the exodus of the Israelites from Egypt led by Moses.
I grew up with that.
The myth is quickly told.
The young Communist Party and its three Red Armies were driven out of their strongholds in the south at the beginning of the 1930s by Chiang Kai-shek's nationalist government.
Pursued and tormented by their enemies, they crossed high mountains, raging rivers, and impassable grazing land, with Mao leading the march from victory to victory.
After two years and 16,000 kilometers of steadfastness, courage, and hope in the face of incredibly bad prospects, the Red Armies reached Northwest China.
Only one-fifth of the 200,000 soldiers had remained – exhausted, badly battered, but full of defiance.
Ten years later, they struck back, defeated Chiang Kai-shek, and founded Mao's New China.
In what extent does China's founding myth stand to reality?
In the year 2004, seventy years after the beginning of the Long March, I embarked on a search for its traces.
It is still a daunting journey through regions that have not changed much to this day, inaccessible and unbelievably poor.
Of the 40,000 survivors, perhaps only 500 are still alive today. I managed to track down 40 of them and conducted conversations with them – they were ordinary people who were left behind or managed to make it to the end, but their stories were extremely enlightening.
Huan Zhiji was still a child, hardly taller than his rifle, when he joined the Red Army.
He had no choice: They had taken his father captive and wouldn't let him go until Huang agreed.
He thought about desertion, but stayed, out of fear of being caught and shot.
Many deserted.
Six weeks after the start of the march, Mao's First Army had shrunk from 86,000 to 30,000 soldiers.
The blame for this loss is still attributed to the Battle of the Xiang River, the first major battle of the army on the march.
However, at most 15,000 died in the battle, the rest disappeared.
Another battle, which took place at Dadu River, is at the center of the legend of the Long March. Apparently, 22 brave men overwhelmed a regiment of nationalist troops who were guarding the chain of the Luding Bridge with machine guns, and cleared the way for the marchers.
Mao told Edgar Snow, the author of Red Star Over China, that crossing the Dadu was the most significant event on the Long March in itself, and it is thus praised today.
However, documents that I have seen indicate that the General who led the division over the Dadu first told the party historians a completely different story. „The matter was not as complicated as people later made it out to be“, he said. „When you examine historical facts, you should respect the truth.
How they present it is a different matter.“
So the legend continues.
There was merely a bit of banter above the dominoes.
The local warlord, who hated Chiang Kai-shek, let Mao pass.
As a reward, he later received a ministerial post in the communist government.
The march participants did not know where they were going along the way.
There were constant discussions about the final goal.
When they met in northern China in October 1936, this was celebrated as the end of the March.
However, the "promised land" was not as promised.
It could hardly feed its own population, let alone the Red Army.
The soldiers had no clothing to protect themselves from the icy cold.
The women were ordered to turn around and return home because there wasn't enough food.
About a month after the unification of the three Red Armies, the Party decided that the Long March had to continue.
However, it was saved by the kidnapping of Chiang Kai-shek by the General appointed by Chiang to destroy the Communists.
As part of the price for his release, Chiang recognized the Communists as legitimate.
The Long March was over.
However, not for the 21,000 men and women of the Western Legion.
They belonged to the Fourth Army, led by Zhang Guotao, Mao's arch-rival, and were tasked with obtaining help from Russia across the western Chinese border.
But Mao gave them contradictory orders, so they could neither fight nor retreat.
Trapped in barren land where survival was difficult, they were eradicated by the superior forces of the Muslim warlords.
Only 400 reached the border, the rest were killed or captured.
It was the greatest defeat of the Red Army.
Yet it is missing from the official historiography.
A Muslim commander took leading officer Wang Quanyan as his mistress.
This was enough to make her in the eyes of the party a traitor and have her deny all the years she had devoted to the army.
She and the other survivors of the Fourth Army had to fight for half a century to be recognized as participants in the march.
The participants of the Long March were steadfast, fought, starved, were desperate, and held on.
Starvation brought the soldiers to take hostages in order to extort ransom money.
The liquidations continued, until practically no officers were left to take command in the battles.
If the marchers were uncertain, they overcame this with the help of communist propaganda.
They took their martyrdom with a courage and self-sacrifice that is unparalleled in the history of China and other peoples.

What drove her to it?
I questioned one of the highest generals at the time about what he knew about communism back then. "I had no idea then, just like now," he replied. "I even doubt that Mao himself knew what it was." For him, who had survived extreme poverty and oppression, communism was a beautiful dream that kept him alive, the hope for a just and progressive society.
No one may have known - or could have known - how much suffering was still to come, how great the sacrifice, and how enormous the difference between the dream and reality would be.
